Moreover, the fluorescence lifetime would decrease a lot owing to excitation-state electron transfer [53]. Time-resolved decay spectra was employed to verity the happening of the excited stated electron transfer, Fig. 8
                        A demonstrated that the excitation fluorescence lifetime decreased dramatically from 62.73 to 16.21 ns after the addition of 10.0 μmol⋅L−1 guanine to CDs-ZnCdTe QDs solution, which meeting the requirements of excited state electron transfer. In brief, electron in valence band (VB) migrated to the conduction band (CB) and left positive holes (h+
                        ) in VB after the excitation of CDs-ZnCdTe QDs [54]. Guanine was rich in electron-donating group (-NH2) and attached to the surface of the CDs-ZnCdTe QDs, the electron from guanine could be easily transferred to the positive holes in VB of QDs, therefore, the non-radiative electron–hole recombination of CDs-ZnCdTe QDs occupied the majority of the recombination process, leading to the quench of fluorescence.
